{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_bison_ver01/data/sn84024808/00295860704/1920102401/0263.xml":{"full_text":"GREAT FALLS DAILY TRIBUNE\nTHIRTY -SECOND YEAR\nGREAT PALLS. MONTANA. SUNDAY MORNING, OCTOBER 24,1920.\nTHIRTY-FOUR PAGES PRICE FIVE CENTS\nPOLITICAL PREACHMENTS HAVE LEAGUE AS TEXT\nCox Predicts Panicky Condition if Covenant is Rejected; Judge Hughes Holds Him in Line with President, Sug\ngcsting Eliminating Disputed Section if Meaningless; Harding Quotes Jefferson, Cleveland and Mr. Wilson on\nAmerican Policies W hich He Says A re Nul lified b y Much Disputed Article X and Queries Rumanian Incident\nRED CROSS RELIEF FOR EUROPE LAS T YEAR TOTALLED $510,00,000\nCITES LEADERS\nT\nDispute Over Helping\nRumania is Theme of\nG. O. P. Nominee.\nMarlon, O., Oct. 23.\u2014Alluding\nfor the first time to the controversy\nbetween President Wilson and Sen\nator Spencer over the former's Paris\nutterances regarding America's part\nin maintaining European peace, Sen\nator Harding said Saturday night\nthat the version of the presidents'\nwords recently published In this\ncountry and attributed to Premier\nBratiano of Rumania served to\nthrow new light on the real char\nacter of article 10.\nThe controversy as to the exact lan\nguage used by Mr. Wilson was not itself\ndiscussed by the Republican nominee\nwho said in reply to a question that it\nwas not his dispute. He added, however,\nthat \"the belated testimony of the Ru\nmanian premier is interesting by way of\nconfirming the president's objections to\namending the league covenant.\"\n\"The president said to several sen\nators.\" he continued, \"for one of whom\nI can speak definitely, that any amend\nment would lead to demands by Rumania\nand other small nations with attending\nembarrassment.\nCouncil Trepassed Rights\n\"All this emphasized our objection to\nthe covenant as written. Clearly the su\npreme council trespassed the rights of\nthe small nations and assumed to de\ncide their very own political and eco\nnomic affairs and then set about to\nmaintain the existing order of things by\nthe rule of force. It has been the Re\npublican purpose all along to establish a\nworld association for the rule of justice\nrather than force.\nEurope Knows Commitment\n\"Clearly, Europe understands that\nwhich we are coming to know, that the\nleague as written commits America to\nthe armed support of the four great\npowers in maintaining the integrity of\ntheir enlarged dominions whenever at\ntacked from without. This is why\nAmerica will vote its unalterable hos\ntility to article 10. When that is done\nwe may seek a new understanding, one\nwhich will hold us unmortgaged to Eu\nrope and the orient.\"\nThe senator made no speeches during\nthe day but in elaborating his comment\non the Bratiano interview he ,-,ave out\nseveral quotations from Thomas Jeffer\nson, Grover Cleveland and Wcodrow\nWilson which he said had a direct bear\ning on the whole Jeague issue.\nQuotes Jefferson\nHe called attention that it. was 97\nyears ago Sunday that Jefferson wrote\nto Monroe:\n\"Our first and fundament maxim\nshould be never to entangle ourselves in\nthe broils of Europe.\"\nThe following he quoted from a r.peecb\nby Cleveland on December S, 1885:\n\"We have foreborne from taking part\nin any controversy between foreign\nstates, but have left, to every nation the\nexclusive conduct and management of\nits own affairs.\"\nMr. Wilson's Statement\nIiis quotation from President Wilson\nwas taken from a newspaper report of\nthe president's words on May 0, 1914,\nand was as follows:\n\"America should lead her own life. We\ncannot form alliances with those who are\nnot going our way. We need not and\nwe should not form alliances with any j\nnation in the world.\"\nIiis comment on these utterances,\nSenator Harding said.\nis\nr n\nTo all Americans, and especially to\nall Democrats, it must appear that\ntide 10 of the League of Nations, which\nwould submerge American nationality\nand independence in an armed alliance\nwearing a mask of benevolent idealism, j\nis a complete reversal, not only of Amir- I\nican, but of Democratic policy.\n\"I don't hesitate to say that T stand to\nby the expressions of Jeffer -ion, Cleve- i a\nland and that of the president, made in i\n1914, for I am unflinchingly opposed to\narticle 10.\"\nbe\nN5T.MLJMF\nAaron Shea, Alias \"Tacoma\nJohnny\" Doyle, Declared\nGuilty as Associate.\nSt. Paul. Oct. 23.\u2014Aaron Shea, alias\n\"Tacoma Johnny\" Doyle, was found\nguilty of murder in the Ramsey county\nd'strict court, late Saturday in connec\ntion with the slaying of Alice McQuillan\nDunn, April 20, 1917, at her home here.\nThe jury received the case late Friday\nIt was charged that Shea was the\nthird man in the slaying. Several others\nare serving penitentiary sentences for\nthe crime. Shea will be sentenced Mon\nday. i\nWilson Hopes Young\nMen Will Support\nWorld War Ideals\nWashington, Oct. 23.\u2014President\nWilson telegraphed the Young Amer\nican's Democratic' league of Columbia\nuniversity his belief that, the young\nmen and women of the country \"will\nrally to the support of the perpetua\ntion of the high ideals for which we\nfought in the great war.\"\n<V >nveying his greetings through\nRolland Bradley to a meeting of the\nYoung American Democratic league\nin New York City, the president said:\n\"The young men and women of the\ncountry should be even more deeply\ninterested in this critical contest than\nother Americans for the issues are\nthe issues of the future.\n\"They will determine the future in\nfluences and greatness of the United\nStates in the counsels of the nation.\nThey will determine our moral force\nin all the great pending contests of\nright with which the world is already\nquick.\"\nLETTS HEADING\nSOVIET\u00dcPSET\nSecret Meetings Said\nHeld in Riga to End\nSoviet Authority.\nRiga., Oct. 22.\u2014Somewhat of a sensa\ntion has boon caused here by a report\nthat a secret conference is being held at\nRiga between representatives of the\nWrangle government and Karl Ullmati,\npremier of Letvia, and M. Meirmwitch,\nthe Letvian foreign minister. It is re\nported they have reached a complete un\nderstanding for ao-operation for the\noverthrow of the Russian soviet gov\nernment. The main points in the agree\nment are said to be that independ\nence will be granted Poland and Letvia\nbecome autonomous parts of Russia\nand that Esthonia and the Ukraine will\nDocuments concerning an alleged\nsecret agreement, addressed to Boris\nSavinkoff, the former military governor\nof Petrograd, at Warsaw, are said to\nhave been found on Count Palem, a Let,\nwhen crossing the German frontier.\nWarsaw, Oct. 23.\u2014Commotion which\nlasted more than an hour followed adop\ntion by the diet, by a majority of six\nvotes, of the clause of the constitution\nproviding for a two chamber parliament.\nLeft, wing socialists and peasant and\nlabor members rapped on their desks\nand sang revolutionary songs as a pro\ntest against the action. Finally the up\nroar reached such a stage that the\nspeaker was compelled to adjourn the\nsitting.\nThe recently elected German members\nfrom Pomrania cast the six deciding\nvotes. Final action on the constitution\nis expected within the next few weeks.\nj\n\nn ol j t j- j- c\nBody Showed Indications of Man\nBeing Taken in Auto and\nBeaten to Death.\nj Washington, Oct. 2\".\u2014Police declared\nI Saturday they \\\\#-e in possession of in\nformation which they expected to lead\nto prompt identification of the body of\ni a man found Friday night on the out\nskirts of Washington and believed to\nbe Major Frank M. Scanland of Louis\nville. Ken., who served with the A. E. F.\nPolice advanced the theory that the\nma n bad been taken to the edge of the\ncity in an automobile, beaten to death\nand bis body dragged into the brush. The\nman apparently had been dead three\ndays.\nWatertown, X. Y., Oct 23\u2014Major\nFrank M. Scanland, found slain near\nAlexandria, Va., last, night, had been in\nthe United States army 35 years. He\nwas stationed at Oswego, X. Y. with the\n23rd infantry in 1913. During the world\nwar he was gassed and recently had been\nundergoing treatment at Fort Bliss,\nTexas.\n2 Convicts Escaping\nFrom Sing Sing Are\nTaken in Mountains\nWarner, X. H., Oct. 23.\u2014George\nStivers and Marcus Bassett. who es\ncaped from Sing Sing prison at Ossin\ning, X Y.. last Saturday night, were\ncaught Friday in the foothills of Kear\nsarge mountains. The men. tired and\nhungrey, surrendered without resistance\nand at night were on their way, back to\nthe prison in custody of prison keeprs.\nBETWEEN 1\nIS HELD FACT\nJudge Hughes Reverts\nto Platform to Prove\nOneness of Purpose,\nNew Haven. Oct. 23.\u2014Wood\nrow Wilson might as well bo tho\nDemocratic candidate for president\nagain this year as Govrenor Cox,\nCharles E. Hughes declared in an\naddress on the League of Nations\nhere Saturday night. \"How vain it\nIs to say that Mr .Cox is runinng for\npresident and not Mr. Wilson,\" he\nexclaimed, adding:\n\"The time has now passed for efforts\nto placate an autocratic executive. Tf\nMr. Cox is going to part company with\nMr. Wilson, and is opposed to article X\nof the league covenant, why should he\nnot frankly say that he favors its elimin\nation?\"\nThe stands of Governor Cox and Pres\nident Wilson are identical to commit the\nLnited States to the league with article\nX and only meaningless reservations,\nMr. JIughes asserted.\nNeither the presidenut nor the gover\nnor have changed their attitude in this\nrespect, and all insinuations and declara\ntions to the contrary are misstatements\nhe added.\n1\nj strenuously insisted.\nRestating Constitutional Method.\n\"As Mr. Wilson says,\" Mr. Hughes\ncontinued, \"to set forth that congress\nalone can declare war, would merelv be\na statement of our constitutional method.\nIt would he, not a denial of the obliga\ntion. but as he said, a statement of the\nway in which we should fulfill it. This\nwould not affect the obligation assumed\nby the treaty upon which Mr. Wilson so\nWhen this nation\nbinds itself by the treaty making power\nto other nations, then it is bound to use\nall its organs according to its own meth\nods for the purpose of performing that\nobligation.\nIf article X were a meaningless form\nof words he would not object to remov\ning it. But he insists upon it because it\ndoes impose an obligation and because\nhe desires the United States to rest tin\nder that obligation. Having secured the\ni imposition of the obligation he ha\nobjection to what he considers a vicious\nstatement as to the way in which we\ndischarge otir obligations.\n\"We come now to the question of the\nattitude of .Mr. Cox and in behalf of his\nabhorrence of \"wobbling\" we may sup\npose that it will exhibit a similar mean\ning of purpose.\nPlatform and Mr. Wilson.\n\"We assume in discussing the attitude\nof the candidate we may properly start\nwith the platform of the Democratic\nparty. I n!ess the Democratic platform\nintended grossly to deceive the people\nit meant to say that the party in\ndorsed President Wilson in his firm\nstand against any reservations which\nwould impair the effectiveness of Ar\ntide Ten. Then what of the candidate?\nDid he not say explicitly that he st,<>od\nupon the Democratic platform? Will\nhe now say that he repudiates the Dem\nocratic platform?\n\"This question came up acutely at\nonce and to settle it Mr. Cox made the\npilgrimage to the White House so that\nthere would be no mistake of the en\ntire concord of the leaders. After his\nvisit to the White House Mr. Cox said:\nGovernor's Statement.\n\u00d6S t meaning\nnd purpose of the Democratic plat- j\nform. 1 resident Wlson announced that i\nhe fourni that he and Governor Cox\nwere absolutely as one with regard to\nthe gi eat issue of the League of Na\n\"r'ri \u00ab.\u2022ii\ne is still u valiant old guard\nw 'hich, ill spite of a complete demon\nI\nI\ni\nstration as to what Article Ten means,\nand its antagonism to our most funda\nmental principles, are determined to re\nsist to the last the assaults of clear\nreasoning. They say Mr. Wilson did\nnot insist upon the agreement without\nchange. They also assert that Mr. Cox\nis willing to accept reservations.\n\"Is it meant that Mr. Wilson is will\ning to agree to reservations which\neliminated the obligation to be assumed\nbv Article Ten? If so, to use their own\nmode of expression, the assertion is false,\ndemons!rably false\nChicago, Oct. 23.\u2014 Virgil (\u00cf. Hinshaw,\nchairman of the Prohibition national com\nmittee, in a statement Thursday denied\nreports which he said were \"flooding his\noffice\" that Aaron S. Wntkins, prohibi\ntion presidential candidate, planned to\nwithdraw from the race.\n\"Early in the campaign we told Mr.\nCox and Mr. Harding that Mr. Watkins\nwould withdraw if either would mak;> an\nopen and specific pledge to oppose legis\nlation which would weaken the Volstead\nact. but neither responded with such a\npledge. An eleventh hour declaration by\neither candidate would not now result in\nthe withdrawal of the Prohibition candi\ndat^ who are in the fight to the finish.\"\nFRENCH AND BELGIAN\nWORK GAVE BENEFIT\nTO 30,000/)00 NEEDY\nActivities Now Confined to Lesser Countries in\ncluding Poland and Russia, Reports State, Need\nEntirely Vanishing in Italy; Trained Assistants\nLeft Where Efforts Terminated.\nWashington, Oct. 24.\u2014The American Red Cross furnished re\nlief to war-stricken Europe during the last year to the amount of\n$51,000,000. The most extensive of overseas activities of the or\nganization, however, ended during the year with the ciosing of re\nlief work in Belgium and France.\nRed Cross work in Europe, according\nto a statement issued from the national\nh'eadquarters here and based on the\nforthcoming report for the year that\nended last June 30, is now confined to\nPoland, Serbia, Montenegro, Albania,\nWest Russia and the Balds states. South\nRussia, Vienna, Budapest and Constan\ntinople.\nIn bringing the work in France and\nBelgium to a close, the Red Cross pro\nvided supplies to 3.863 villages and di\nrectly benefitted 30.000.000 persons by\ngifts or sales at nominal prices. In\nItaly the need of direct relief practical\nly vanishel and the Red Cross confined\nits work there to home service for Amer\nican soldiers and their families and the\nfounding of welfare institutions for\nchildren.\nLocal self-help ran hand-in-liand with\nthe Red Cross relief and whenever the\nAmerican organization withdrew from a\nterritory it left a sufficient body of train\ned workers among the people to carry\non the activities.\nPolish War Zone.\nIn the war zone of northern Poland\nt>\u201e,i e nr.u i\nthe Red Cross \"established 25.S hospitals\nof 26,123 beds, aided 30 established\ndispensaries and helped establish S2\nothers. It distributed clothing to 80,\n000 children and gave general relief to\n2,316 towns with a population of more\nthan 700,<HM>. In southern Poland, more\nthan 1,000 hospitals and charitable in\nstitutions got assistance from the Red\nCross. j\nThe work in Rumania consisted of op\nNoted French Specialist Was\nCalled for Administering to\nStricken Monarch.\nAthens, Oct. 23.\u2014King Alexander of\nGreece, who is critically ill as a result\n\na trained nurse, remains at the king's\nbedside night and day. fighting for his\nlifo with ail the skill and experience she\ngained during the war.\nPremier Venizelos has gone to Kep\nhisia, near the royal country house at\nTatoi, where the king is staying, to be\njn closer touch with the situation.\nof infection caused by the bite of a\ni I\nmonkey, entered a very acute cerebral!,\ncrisis Saturday. His condition was des\ncribed by his physicians as most critical.!\nj\nParis, Oct. 23.\u2014Dr. Georges Fernand j\nWidal, a noted French specialist, has j\nreturncd here from Athens, where he\nattended King Alexander. It is under- j\nstood he treated the king with injections\nof serum prepared from the wound it-\nself. j\nThe morganatic wife of the king. I\nknown as Madeinoselle Manos. who was j\nICULTU1\nThree Representatives to Inter\nnational Conference Go From\nUnited States.\nWashington, Oct. 23.\u2014Three of the\ndelegates from the United States to the\ngeneral assembly of the international\ninstitute of agriculture at Rome which\nmeets November 3 to 15. were announced\nSaturday by the department of agri\nculture. They are:\nDr. Thomas F. Hunt, dean of the col\nlege of agriculture of the University of\nCalifornia, who has been named perma\nnent. delegate to succeed the late David\nLubin; Lon M. Estabrook, chief of the\nbureau of crop estimates, department, of\nagriculture and Harvey .1. Sconce, Siiie\nhill, Illinois, former president of the Illi\nnois agriculture association and organ\nizer of the American Farm Bureau Fed\neration.\nBOSTON SUB-TREASURY CLOSED.\nWashington, Oct. 23.\u2014Secretary\nHouston Saturday ordered the discon\ntinuance of the sub-treasury at Boston\neffective October 25.\nera ting hospitals and dispensaries, pro\nj viding supplies to schools and orphanag\n\nes, conducting soup kitchens that fed\n100.000 people and in distributing dry\nfood to more than 170,000 others.\nIn Thrace and Smyrna\nT ho society distributed 40,000 gar\nments in Greece proper, 10 ,000 blankets;\nand Svmrna^mTrtO (MM^garmen^s^to'the\ncolonies in Asia Minor. Relief work in\nSerbia was not extensive, the statement\nsays although much disease preventive\nwork was necessary to insure the future\nhealth of the nation.\nIn Albania the society opened five\nmedical dispensaries, four dental dis\npensaries and numerous infant welfare\nand milk stations. In additions to\nhelping practically the entire popula\ntion in the villages, it distributed 96,\n000 garments among the hill tribes. In\nMontenegro, 30,000 orphans are today\nbeing cared for by agencies which draw\ntheir supplies largely from the Red\nCross. Two child-feeding station\u00ab, with\na capacity of 300,000 meals\nmonth.\nalso are being operated by the American\norganization.\nIn Vienna, aid was given to 9.8 hos\npitals. and 40,000 under-nourished oh il-\ndren were fed by the Red Cross, while\nin Budapest aid was also given to hos-\npitals and thousands of children. In\nConstantinople, the work was confined\nto t are, feeding, clothing and medical\ntreatment of Russian and other refugees.\nwho passed through the Bosphorus j\nlast winter.\nPolice Charge George (r. Iioyd,\nFormer Colorado Convict,\nWith Daring Hold-up.\nSpokane, Oct. 23.\u2014A warrant charg\nj ing George C. Boyd with the robberv\nrT\u201e;\u201e\u201e i,\u201e\u201ei n\nj i ne i mon t s k bank here last l uosfiav\nu\nI \u00eeas Pn issued, according to information\nbj police officials here Saturday.\ni-oyd is charged also with the robbe-y\n11 bank at Starbuck, Washington, last\n\u2022'\"'.V \"\"d the reported similarity in mcth\ns fhe robberies led, it was stated,\nto Boyd s identification by police officers\nan employes of the bank here as the\nrobber of the local bank. Boyd, who\nescaped from the state penitentiary in\nColorado in 1018, is said to have rela\nfives at alla alia.\nPresident-Elect of\nMexico is Pleased\nOver Texas Greeting\nMexico City, Oct. 23.\u2014General Alvaro\nObregon. president-elect of Mexico, re\nturned from Dallas. Tex., Friday and\ntold interviewers he was impressed by\nthe cordiality of the reception given him\nthere. He declared he looked upon it\nns indicating, a phanged opinion toward\nMexico on the part of Americans.\nThe president-elect laughed at reports\nthat a plot against his life had been dis\ncovered in Texas.\nMINNESOTA TOWN IS AFIRE\nLa Crosse, Wis., Oct. 23.\u2014Fire be\nlieved to have started in a warehouse\nlate Saturday night, spread to Smith's\nhotel and the postoffice, at Browns\nville, Minn., 12 miles south of here, ac\ncording to reports received here. Wire\ncommunication with the village was cut\nwhen the telephone exchange burned.\nFire fighting apparatus has been sent\nfrom this city.\nl\nMELSTONE BANK IS ROBBED\nBY LONE YEGG AT NOON TIME\nLewistown, Oct. 23.\u2014At noon Saturday a lon\u00e8 robber entered\nthe Mel stone State Bank, at Melstone, one of the large towns in\nMusselshell county, on the main line of the Milwaukee railroad, and\nat the point of a gun forced the bookkeeper, Mr. Dunvas, and a\nsmall boy into the vault and locked them in. He then gathered all\nthe money in sight and on leaving mounted a horse which he had\ntied near the bank and rode away. Mr. Dunvas was able to give an\nalarm in a short time and at night a large posse of officers and cit\nizens is chasing the robber. The amount of cash taken is said to\nbe $\u00a3,000.\nBUSINESS DEPRESSION SURE\n10 FOLLOW REJECTING PACT\nIS STATED BY GOVERNOR COX\nMadison Square Garden Filled to Capacity by\nAudience Receiving Candidate's Assurances on\nTaking Versailles Covenant With Reservations;\nFinancial Power of America Held Sufficient to\nOffset Any Demand for Sending Army Abroad.\nNew York, Oct. 23.\u2014Governor Cox of Ohio delivered his\nT r XT x.\nea ue Nations message to a great audience m Madison Square\nGarden Saturday night and, emphasizing business and economic\nconsi <Jerations, declared that \"America's successful future depends\non entrance into the league at the earliest possible moment.\"\nj\nI. C. C. Revokes Order\nOn Cars Allotted to\nMeet Urgent Need.\nWashington, Oct. 23.\u2014The interstate\nCommerce Commission discontinued Sat\nurday preferential allotments of coal\ncars for fuel transportation to the Great\nLakes district in three sections of the\ncountry. Allotments are to be omitted\nat the junctionof the Louisville Nasb\nville railroad, in the Irwin Gas-Coal\ndistrict of Pennsylvania and in the nor\nthern Ohio district, the middle districts\nof Ohio, and also the Butler-Mercer\ndistricts in Pennsylvania.\nIn addition, the commission announced\ncoal ear allotments may be ominited\nagainst wagon mines and mines produc\ning stripper coal until further notice.\nCoal at lake ports for trans-shipment\nto the northwest has been delivered in\nsufficient quantities, offidals said, to\npermit a reduction of this movement,\nand a greater supply will be available in\nthe districts affected by the order and\nalso for public utilities.\nE\nDunn Jumps 4 Stories, Sprains\nAnkle, Plunges Into River\nTo Avoid Arrest.\nI\nI\nSpokane, Oct, 23\u2014James Dunn, 28,\nwas suffering from a fractured ankle j\nSa tu rday after a flight from local police j\nofficers Friday night that included al-\nmost enough narrow escapes for a j\n\"movie thriller.\" j\nThey comprised a fall of four stories j\nfrom a hotel window when a sheet rope I\nbroke, a race of two blocks with his\ninjured ankle, and a plunge into the j\nrapids of the Spokane river from a\nbridge.\nAccording to the police. Dunn fled\nfrom a room where two other men were\narrested and a quantity of drugs and\ndrug-users appliances were seized.\nI00 KILLED IN RAIL WRECK\nTokio, Oct. 23. \u2014Special dispatches\nfrom Harbin, Manchuria, report casu\nalties in killed and injured in a collision\nof train on the Chinese Eastern rail\nway near Harbin. The victims, the re\nports add, were Russians.\nWillingness to make \"some compro\nmise\" on league reservations was de\ndared by the Democratic presidential\ncandidate. lie reiterated that he would\naccept \"helpful reservations.\" If elect\ned. he said he \"would lift this issue out\nof politics by affecting 'a result which\nwill insure the entrance of the United\nStates into the league, with the idea of\nperfecting it and obtaining for ourselves\nthe benefits which will accrue.\"\nGovernor Cox's speech,\" closing his\neastern campaign and climaxing a day of\nreceptions, luncheons and other events,\nstressed agricultural, industrial, banking\nand other arguments foe American par\nticipation in the league.\n\"The most serious depression the\ncountry has ever witnessed\" was pre\ndicted by the nominee if the league cause\nwas lost. Business depression already,\nhe declared, \"has grown intense\" as a\nresult of Senator allrding's statements\non his league attitude.\nReiterating that financial rehabilita\ntion credit and power together with in\ncreased resources resulting from disarm\nament, would flow from the league's suc\ncess. Governor Cox declared.\n\"If we go into the league, our finan\ncial power will guarantee that we 'hall\nnever have to send an American army\nto fight in Europe. f f '.ve meet the op\nportunity that calls to us. we can write\nthe word 'American' across the page of\nthe twentieth cent'iry history in letters\nof light.\"\nRegarding compromising on league res\nervations, he said:\n\"It is going to be necessary to make\nsome compromise to secure the desired\nend, and that I am willing t> do. i am\nfor the ratification of the league with\nreservations and have so stated my po\nsition in every speech made from the\nAtlantic to the Pacific. I will accept\nreservations that are helpful, that will\nclarify, that will reassure our own peo\nple and that will make clear to our as\nsociates in the league the limitations of\notir constitution, beyond which we can\nnot go, among which are the Hitchcock\nreservations.\"\nCiting Senator Hitchcock's reserva\ntion to article ten. Governor Cox re\npeated that he would consider his elec\ntion a \"mandate\" for entrance into the\nleague and that he would sit down with\nthe senate and endeavor to reach an\nagreement \"with as little conversation\nas possible.\"\n\"And from my experience as a legis\ni lator,\" the nominee said, \"I am confid\nent that we will have action,\nj \"Xo suggestion from whatever source\nI will be regretted so long as that sugges\ntion is for helpful purposes and not for\ndestruction.\"\nAnother promise made by Governor\nCox was, that realizing necessity for\nreforming federal agencies, he would not\nhesitate to call on any man for aid, re\ngardless of his politics.\n\"As an executive of some experience,\nresult of knowledge gained as\nas\nmember of the appropriation committeo\nin congress and as a business man, who\nhas spent days and nights to make tho\nledger balance, I am keenly aware of the\nnecessity to approve and modernize tho\nexecutive machinery of our federal gov\nernment and to bring into contact the\nbest brains and experience America con\ntains\" he said.\nDry Law's Repeal in\nB. C. Requires Strict\nWashington Statutes\nTacoma, Oct. 23.\u2014\"The repeal of\n'bone dry' prohibition in Briitsh Columbia\nmakes necessary a more drastic prohib\nition law in this state.\" Commissioner\nof Public Safety Fred Shoemaker said\nSaturday. Mr. Shoemaker said the next\nlegislature will be asked to strengthen\nthe state law.\nWyoming Governor\nRefused to Settle\nNation's League Day\nCheyenne, Wyo.. Oct. 23.\u2014Taking th#\nposition it would be just as reasonable\nto Call for observance of a \"tariff day\"\nor \"high cost of living day\" or one com\nmemorating any other issue of the pres\nent, campaign. Governor Robert D. Carey\nSaturday refused to proclaim Sunday\n\"League of Nations Sunday\" for Wyom\ning. His telegram of refusal sent to the\nLeague of Nations day committee in New\nl^rk was made public.","height":"22896","width":"17784"}}
